s directly intervened in the wider discourse of communication studies, as it manifested in the politics of countercultural dropout, soft power and cultural diplomacy, alternative pedagogies, sociological art and feminist consciousness-raising.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspects. 0aHappenings (Art). 0aPerformance artxHistory. 0aPerformance artxPsychological aspects. 0aPerformance art. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aBody art.  aCommunication.  aCybernetics.  aFeminism.  aHappenings.  aInternationalism.  aParticipation.  aPerformance.  aPsychology.  aSociology.1 aSpencer, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614446140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526144461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526144461/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles